My recommended order                                    
                                                            
  1. Mobile-first pass across all tabs (~1-2 hrs of edits).
  Most SHS students open this on phones. I'd audit
  AnalysisDashboard, StudyCoach, Leaderboard,
  CompetitionPortal at 360px–414px widths, fix layout
  breaks, touch-target sizes, and scroll behaviour. Highest
  leverage.
  2. Empty & error states (~30 min). Right now if generation
   fails, the history is empty, or the quiz code doesn't
  exist, you mostly get a spinner-that-stops or a silent
  blank. Replace each with a friendly "nothing here yet"
  illustration or "couldn't load — tap to retry" pattern.
  3. Loading skeletons (~30 min). Swap the full-page
  spinners for content-shaped shimmer placeholders on
  subject-list load, exam history, leaderboard. Feels 3×
  faster even at identical real latency.
  4. Design-system consistency sweep (~45 min). A lot of
  buttons use hand-rolled Tailwind classes with slight drift
   (border-radius, shadow levels, hover states). Extract a
  couple of shared button/card primitives and consolidate,
  which also shrinks the bundle.
  5. Dark mode completeness + theme toggle — your memory
  says dark mode CSS was added for major surfaces but
  there's no visible toggle UI. Either expose the toggle or
  drop dark mode until you have one.
  6. Performance: audit bundle size (manualChunks is already
   set up per your memory), lazy-load non-critical routes,
  add image lazy-loading.

  Tradeoff

  Doing all six would take ~4-5 hours of edits. The biggest
  user-visible win per minute is (1) + (2) + (3) — those
  three together transform the app from "functional" to
  "polished" for about half the total effort. Items (4)–(6)
  are quality-of-life engineering that users won't
  consciously notice but will feel.

  Recommendation: start with 1 → 2 → 3 as a bundle. Say the
