  =====================================================================
  DESIGN DIRECTION — Ghana-proud, modern, world-class, scalable
  =====================================================================

  GOAL

  Make the app feel like it was built in Accra — not a generic
  SaaS template translated to Ghana. Students should recognise
  it as *theirs*. That means a design language rooted in Ghana's
  visual identity, executed with the restraint and precision of
  Linear / Stripe / Vercel. Bold enough to feel proud, quiet
  enough to study in for three hours.


  1. COLOR SYSTEM (Ghana-inspired, premium-adapted)

  Do NOT use Ghana flag colors at full saturation — those read
  "government website". Use deeper, desaturated interpretations
  that feel premium and allow long reading sessions.

  Core tokens (add to :root in index.css):

    /* Ghana-identity primaries */
    --gh-forest:    #0B6E4F;   /* deepened flag green, primary */
    --gh-forest-600:#0F5A42;   /* hover / pressed */
    --gh-forest-50: #E6F2ED;   /* tinted surface */

    --gh-brass:     #C99B3A;   /* warm gold, accents only */
    --gh-brass-600: #A67E28;
    --gh-brass-50:  #FAF1DC;

    --gh-ember:     #B8202C;   /* flag red, error/danger only */
    --gh-ember-50:  #FBE7E9;

    /* Surfaces — warm neutrals, not clinical white */
    --gh-cream:     #FAF7F0;   /* app background (ivory, not white) */
    --gh-paper:     #FFFFFF;   /* raised cards */
    --gh-chalk:     #F1ECE1;   /* subtle dividers */

    /* Text */
    --gh-ink:       #1A1A1A;   /* primary text (warm black, not pure) */
    --gh-ink-60:    #4A4A4A;   /* secondary */
    --gh-ink-40:    #7A7A7A;   /* tertiary */

    /* Dark mode mirror */
    --gh-night:     #0E1713;   /* background (forest at 3% lightness) */
    --gh-night-raised: #162520;
    --gh-gold-glow: #E5B84B;   /* brass lifted for dark backgrounds */

  Usage rules:
  - Forest green: primary actions, brand mark, active state.
  - Brass gold: earned / premium / "success with prestige"
    (access-code unlock, passing grade ≥80%, leaderboard top 3).
  - Ember red: errors only, never decoration. If it doesn't
    require the user's attention, it doesn't get red.
  - Cream as background instead of pure white — warmer, more
    paper-like, easier on phone screens in sun glare.


  2. TYPOGRAPHY (already 70% there)

  Current stack:
  - Outfit (headings, UI) ✅
  - Patrick Hand (handwriting feel for questions) ✅
  - KaTeX math fonts ✅

  Add one more:
  - Inter Tight 540-560 weight for long-form body text
    (StudyCoach answers, tutor chat). Outfit at small sizes on
    Android browsers renders slightly thin; Inter Tight is
    crisper below 15px.

  Scale (pick from, use consistently):
    text-xs  11px  / caption
    text-sm  13px  / secondary
    text-base 15px / body
    text-lg  17px  / emphasis
    text-xl  20px  / subheading
    text-2xl 24px  / section heading
    text-3xl 32px  / page heading
    text-5xl 48px  / hero only

  Line-height: 1.55 body, 1.2 headings. Letter-spacing: 0 body,
  -0.01em headings ≥ text-2xl.


  3. VISUAL MOTIFS (subtle, not themed-school-project)

  Use ONE Adinkra symbol as a repeating brand detail — not
  decorated everywhere. Best fits:

  - Sankofa (bird looking backward) — "learn from the past."
    Perfect for the exam-history / past-questions tabs. Use as
    20% opacity watermark on empty-history state, or as the
    loading-spinner icon instead of a generic Loader2.

  - Nyansapo (wisdom knot) — for the StudyCoach / tutor icon.

  - Dwennimmen (ram's horns, strength & humility) — for
    competition / leaderboard.

  Execution: ship as inline SVG components (not images) so they
  inherit currentColor and scale cleanly. Use them sparingly —
  one per surface, at 10-20% opacity when decorative, full
  opacity only as a brand anchor (nav logo).

  Kente patterns as full backgrounds = do NOT. It reads kitsch.
  If you want Kente, use it as a 4px-tall horizontal accent
  stripe above headers or on the auth modal — a whisper, not
  a shout.


  4. WORLD-CLASS UX PRINCIPLES

  a) Motion tells the story
     - Every state change animates (150-250ms, ease-out).
     - Generate Paper → modal scales in from the button.
     - Correct answer → checkmark draws in with stroke
       animation. Wrong answer → gentle shake.
     - Use `transform` and `opacity` only; avoid layout thrash.

  b) Haptic-feeling feedback (no actual haptics on web)
     - Buttons: 60ms scale-to-98% on active state.
     - Cards: 120ms lift (-2px translateY + shadow deepen) on
       hover, return on leave.

  c) Progressive disclosure
     - Dashboard shows the 12 most-common WASSCE subjects by
       default. A "Show all 59" button reveals the full list.
     - Question cards show question + options; answer +
       explanation hidden behind a "Reveal" toggle until
       submitted.

  d) Zero dead ends
     - Every error has a retry action.
     - Every empty state has a next action ("You haven't
       generated a paper yet. [Generate your first] →").
     - Every loading state has an estimate + a "Cancel".

  e) Offline resilience
     - Cache the subjects list, last generated paper, and
       exam history in localStorage. Ghana networks drop; the
       app should still read like it works.


  5. SCALABILITY — design-system layer

  The biggest blocker to scaling the UI is that buttons and
  cards are hand-rolled per component, with 4-5 nearly-identical
  styles floating around. Fix this before adding more screens.

  Structure to build (small, 1-2 hours):

    frontend/src/components/ui/
      Button.tsx        variants: primary | secondary | ghost
                                  | danger | success
                        sizes:    sm | md | lg
                        states:   loading, disabled, icon-only
      Card.tsx          variants: elevated | outlined | inset
      Badge.tsx         variants: forest | brass | ember
                                  | neutral
      Input.tsx         variants: default | error
                        add-ons:  prefix, suffix, helper text
      Section.tsx       page wrapper with consistent padding
      EmptyState.tsx    icon slot + title + description +
                        action slot
      ErrorState.tsx    retry action, support link
      Skeleton.tsx      shimmer placeholder, shape variants

  Use class-variance-authority (cva) so variants don't drift.
  Result: new screens get consistent look in half the code, and
  redesigns become one-file changes instead of grep-sweeps.

  Tokens file (design tokens as TS, not just CSS):

    frontend/src/lib/tokens.ts
      export const colors = { gh: { forest, brass, ... } }
      export const spacing = { ... }
      export const radii = { sm: 6, md: 10, lg: 16, xl: 24 }
      export const shadows = { sm, md, lg, brandGlow }
      export const motion = { fast: 150, base: 250, slow: 400 }

  Then a Tailwind config layer that re-exports those tokens so
  utility classes stay in sync with the design-system
  primitives.


  6. MOBILE-FIRST NON-NEGOTIABLES (Ghana context)

  - Minimum touch target: 44×44px (Apple HIG) / 48×48dp (Google).
  - Font size minimum: 15px body, 13px caption. Anything smaller
    is unreadable on a 5" Android screen in daylight.
  - Horizontal scrolling: forbidden. If content overflows, wrap
    or truncate with a "more" affordance.
  - Inputs must trigger correct mobile keyboard types
    (`inputMode="numeric"` for access codes, `type="email"`
    for auth, etc).
  - Every tap region: ≥ 8px from adjacent tap regions.
  - Page weight budget: 200KB JS gzipped on the first paint.
    Lazy-load everything else.


  7. EXECUTION ORDER (if doing the full design modernization)

  Phase A (2 hrs) — Foundation
    - Add color tokens + Inter Tight font to index.css
    - Create ui/ primitives (Button, Card, EmptyState, Skeleton)
    - Replace AnalysisDashboard buttons/cards with primitives
      (proof-of-concept)

  Phase B (2 hrs) — Mobile + states
    - Mobile audit at 360/414px (the three main tabs)
    - Wire EmptyState / ErrorState / Skeleton everywhere
    - Fix touch targets and input modes

  Phase C (1 hr) — Identity
    - Pick Adinkra motif, convert to SVG component
    - Apply as Sankofa history watermark, Nyansapo study icon
    - Add Kente accent stripe to auth modal (optional)

  Phase D (1 hr) — Motion + polish
    - Add framer-motion for modal/page transitions
    - Button haptic-feel, card lift
    - Loading shimmer replaces spinners

  Total: ~6 hours of focused editing.